This page is a supplementary teaching scaffold for binding-backed external code.

## Core concept

A compiler can expose typed symbols for code implemented outside the source language, then defer runtime integration to target planning.

## Beanstalk boundary

External import providers create stable binding-backed interfaces before AST consumes visibility.

Per-function link facts identify reachable external calls.

The build system owns provider caches and resolution state for one build. The builder later plans:

- shared runtime assets
- required module specifiers
- entry-specific wrappers
- import preambles and import-map entries

Unused external functions do not generate glue.

External packages expose opaque types, constants and free functions. Method-style APIs use source-owned wrappers.

## Rewrite focus

Explain foreign-function interfaces, symbol identity, capability metadata, demand-driven linking and why provider parsing is not backend source rediscovery.

Canonical details live in both architecture authorities.
